node.text:
Sarcopenia is the diminishing of muscle mass with age. Between the ages of 20 and 80 years, 30% of muscle mass is lost. An #NSFfunded investigation with #Stanford and #palo-alto-veterans-institute-for-research-pavir is using the one-of-a-kind environment of the #ISS to help those suffering #sarcopenia back here on Earth.

Learn more here https://www.issnationallab.org/iss360/ng-crs16-nsf-tissue-engineering-research-age-related-muscle-loss/ or contact @SpaceGinger321 with questions!

node.title: Northrop Grumman CRS-16: National Science Foundation Tissue Engineering

node.text:
Join us for our 10th annual conference! From #tissuechips to #STEM and #astronauts to  #SlimeinSpace, there is going to be something for everybody. It's free and virtual so come join us as we talk space with people who've been there!

Click the link in our bio to register and check out the agenda so you don't miss a single thing!

node.text:
From #ESA #astronaut Thomas Pesquet come these beautiful images of the #moon captured from one of the windows on the #ISS #Cupola. This dome-shaped observatory has 7 windows and allows the crew onboard the most spectacular views of #Earth and #space. We're pretty sure that we'd be spending ALOT of time there!
Fun fact: #NASA astronaut Kjell Lindgren once tweeted that the Cupola has an uncanny resemblance to an Imperial TIE Fighter. The view has even been compared to that of the #MillenniumFalcon! #starwars #viewsfromspace #windowtotheworld #spaceforeverybody
Image credit: NASA

node.text:
The international crew of Expedition 65 is living and working on groundbreaking research all while travelling at 17,600 miles an hour 250 miles above Earth. In the front row from left are, flight engineers Mark Vande Hei, Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov. In the back are, flight engineers Thomas Pesquet, Megan McArthur and Shane Kimbrough with Commander Akihiko Hoshide.  We thank them for all they do to benefit life here on Earth and in space. 
Image credit: NASA

Twice in the last week, #astronauts have ventured outside the #ISS to upgrade the station's power by installing new solar arrays. NASA astronaut Shane Kimbrough and Thomas Pesquet from the European Space Agency have spent close to 14 hours outside the orbiting lab as it sped over #Earth at 17,500 miles an hour! Check out these amazing (and frightening?) images from the most recent spacewalks! Sometimes we think "Wow...yes!!" and other times "Hmmm...we’re not so sure!" What do YOU think?
Image credit: NASA

Who saw the partial #solareclipse this morning? Check it out as the #sun rises to the left of the US Capitol Building, and behind the #Delaware Breakwater Lighthouse, and from Arlington, Virginia. There is little question why this is known as a "ring of fire" solar eclipse!

The 10th annual International Space Station Research and Development Conference (ISSRDC) is open for registration! ISSRDC brings together researchers, engineers, entrepreneurs, investors, and the general public to discuss the benefits of space-based research and technology development and showcase the critical work being done on the orbiting laboratory! 
Information and registration is here: https://www.issconference.org/
